<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How are XML attributes handled in JSON?", answer: "XML attributes are converted to JSON properties with an @ prefix. For example, <book id=\"1\"> becomes {\"book\": {\"@id\": \"1\"}}. This convention clearly distinguishes attributes from child elements in the JSON output. The @ prefix is a widely adopted convention used by several XML-to-JSON conversion libraries." },
  { question: "How are repeated XML elements handled?", answer: "When multiple sibling elements share the same name, they are automatically grouped into a JSON array. For example, <items><item>A</item><item>B</item></items> becomes {\"items\": {\"item\": [\"A\", \"B\"]}}. Single elements remain as plain values, and repeated elements become arrays. This is the most common convention for representing XML sequences in JSON." },
  { question: "What happens to XML text content in JSON?", answer: "If an element contains only text and no attributes or children, the text becomes a simple JSON string value. If an element has both text content and attributes or children, the text is stored under a special #text key. For example, <name lang=\"en\">John</name> becomes {\"@lang\": \"en\", \"#text\": \"John\"}." },
  { question: "Why is XML to JSON conversion not perfectly reversible?", answer: "XML has concepts that JSON cannot represent: element ordering is meaningful in XML but JSON object keys have no guaranteed order, XML distinguishes between attributes and elements while JSON has only key-value pairs, XML supports namespaces and processing instructions, and XML mixed content (text interspersed with elements) is difficult to map to JSON. Converting JSON back to XML may produce a different structure than the original." },
  { question: "What are the common XML to JSON conversion conventions?", answer: "Several conventions exist: BadgerFish preserves all XML information including namespaces and ordering. Parker (or Ray) is minimal, discarding attributes and using the simplest possible JSON. GData (Google Data) uses $t for text content. This tool uses a practical middle ground: @ for attributes, #text for mixed content text, and arrays for repeated elements." }
]) %>

